WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.300
Hi, my name is Maya Gans, and in this talk, I want to tell you how to start your own virtual

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:20.719
book club. So this idea came to me in the beginning of lockdown, I found myself feeling

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:26.639
really alone. And also scrolling through Twitter, I saw everyone taking on these new exciting

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:31.639
hobbies. Like remember the time when there were so many pictures of sourdough. So I was

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:36.919
looking at my bookshelf, and I saw Advanced R. And I realized that's a book that I use

00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:42.540
as a reference, but I never read cover to cover. So I wanted to use the lockdown opportunity

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.919
to do that. And I found myself asking a lot of questions that I didn't have the answers

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:55.080
to. So I reached out to John Harmon, the moderator of the R for Data Science Slack channel. And

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.639
he allowed me to start a book club channel within that Slack and to kind of just see

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:06.480
what happens. And the results were magical. 12 of us ended up meeting weekly for the entirety

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:10.680
of the book. So I think over the course of 25 weeks, and we went from essentially a group

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:17.879
of strangers to now a group of really good friends. So first, I want to talk about the

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:25.279
cornerstones of why I think that this worked. And the reasons are twofold. We created a

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:31.639
microcosm within an already existing community. So you might say there's already R ladies

00:01:31.639 --> 00:01:38.540
or other chapters and groups out there. And that's true. But that's thousands of faceless

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:44.160
group members who, albeit, are extremely helpful and inviting. Whereas this group was 12 of

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:51.120
us meeting on Zoom with the camera on and really humanizing this learning experience

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:56.080
with each other. The other component was that we made this as asynchronous compatible as

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:02.480
possible. So each meeting was recorded and put on YouTube. So if you couldn't attend,

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:07.599
you can watch that. But we also had this Slack channel for people to ask questions and even

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:11.919
answer them whenever they get to them. So you weren't really limited in lockdown to

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:21.440
this single hour. Now, the meetings themselves kind of changed over time what we did with them.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.399
In the beginning, we took the first 30 or so minutes to review what we found in the chapter,

00:02:28.399 --> 00:02:34.880
and then use the rest of the time to answer questions. But after a couple weeks, maybe

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:41.440
around week eight or so, I was getting kind of bored with this model. And I wanted to make an

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:47.600
application. I made a Shiny app that uses the concepts within a chapter. And granted,

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:55.199
this Shiny app was super buggy, didn't even work. But within the hour, we all debugged it together

00:02:55.199 --> 00:03:00.240
and got it up and running. And I think that was kind of a paradigm shift where people started,

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:07.039
rather than just relaying information, they showed us their packages or other creations.

00:03:07.039 --> 00:03:15.520
And it was incredibly inspiring and eye-opening to see how people are using these fundamentals

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:25.440
in these chapters. So now let's get to the secret sauce of why I think this model worked, right?

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:31.520
We're not the first people to make a book club. And I think it's because of two things. One is

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:38.639
that we have a facilitator for each of our books. And in this case, it was me, who, granted, I'm

00:03:38.639 --> 00:03:43.839
pretty extroverted, and I was totally fine pinging people on Slack and being like, hey, it's Thursday

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:50.320
night, time to meet. But you don't have to be that pushy. Rather, the point of the facilitator is that

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:56.960
every week, there is an agenda. And if no one is able to give that presentation for that week,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:04:01.759
then the onus is on the presenter to take that upon themselves, or else the book might kind of

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:11.119
like falter to the wayside. The other component is collaborative infrastructure. And for our case,

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:17.679
we use GitHub. And this image, as well as the text before this, are links. So feel free to

00:04:19.119 --> 00:04:25.279
go out to our GitHub. But our GitHub is three folders. The first is our presentations. So

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:34.959
the actual markdown presentations from each week. The second folder contains a bookdown of all the

00:04:34.959 --> 00:04:39.440
questions and answers collated from the Slack channel, so that you don't have to sift through

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:47.519
that. And the last folder is a data folder. And in this folder, we kind of took that concept of

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:54.559
applications and took a dataset and drilled down into it, where each chapter, we applied that to

00:04:54.559 --> 00:05:04.959
this dataset of our own. Now, to talk about side dishes. So when we started this book club,

00:05:04.959 --> 00:05:10.720
at the outset, the goal was essentially learn the contents of the chapters. But we ended up

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:18.559
learning all of these external things, as well. So I personally onboarded people onto how to

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:24.079
use GitHub in a collaborative sense and collaborate on a single project. We also

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:31.279
learned a lot about our markdown, HTML and CSS. And lastly, and maybe even most importantly,

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:37.600
we were still leveling up on our presentation skills in these times where we're all isolated

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:46.880
and alone. So I want to leave you now with a recipe card, essentially, to recreate this recipe

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:54.320
that worked for us. And the recipe here is kind of, I broke it down into seven steps.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:06:01.519
The first is pick a book. What book do you want to learn? The second is find an online community

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:08.640
to make this as asynchronous as possible. The third is to blast it on social media.

00:06:09.279 --> 00:06:15.679
The fourth is some books are, you know, have natural breaks that might not be the chapters,

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:24.640
so you might chop them into segments that are logical breaks. And then, you know, take a pulse

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:29.440
on the group and on yourself and see what's working in that precious hour that you're

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:36.399
meeting together. And don't be afraid to switch it up. Then lastly, I think it was really awesome

00:06:36.399 --> 00:06:42.000
and fun that we utilized applications of the chapter rather than just keeping it theoretical.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.839
And of course, in the end, have fun. So there's a link to the Slack channel here because I would

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:52.880
really like, if you are going to create a book club, to just let us know what works and what

00:06:52.880 --> 00:07:02.160
didn't. And thank you so much for listening to this talk.

